---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Numerical Methods · Virtual Labs · AquinTutor" description="Six computing virtual experiments — root finding, interpolation, numerical integration, ODE solvers, linear systems and least-squares curve fitting — all hand-rolled in JavaScript with live convergence, error and animation.">
<style>
  .nmx { background:#0a0a0c; color:#e8e8ee; min-height:100vh; font-family:'Geist Mono',ui-monospace,monospace; }
  .nmx .wrap { max-width:1280px; margin:0 auto; padding:36px 22px 90px; }
  .nmx .back { display:inline-flex; align-items:center; gap:7px; font-size:11px; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#9aa0aa; text-decoration:none; margin-bottom:26px; }
  .nmx .back:hover { color:#67e8f9; }
  .nmx .eyebrow { font-size:11px; letter-spacing:0.2em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#67e8f9; font-weight:700; margin-bottom:12px; }
  .nmx h1 { font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; font-size:40px; font-weight:600; letter-spacing:-0.02em; line-height:1.1; margin:0 0 12px; color:#f3f3f8; }
  .nmx h1 em { color:#a78bfa; font-style:italic; }
  .nmx .lede { color:#9aa0aa; max-width:840px; font-size:13.5px; line-height:1.65; margin-bottom:26px; }

  .nmx .shell { display:grid; grid-template-columns:262px minmax(0,1fr); gap:20px; align-items:start; }
  @media (max-width:920px) { .nmx .shell { grid-template-columns:1fr; } }

  .nmx .sidebar { background:#11131a; border:1px solid #2a2a35; border-radius:12px; padding:12px; position:sticky; top:18px; }
  .nmx .sidebar .stitle { font-size:9px; letter-spacing:0.18em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#67e8f9; font-weight:700; margin:4px 6px 10px; }
  .nmx .exp-item { display:flex; gap:9px; align-items:flex-start; padding:9px 10px; border-radius:8px; cursor:pointer; border:1px solid transparent; transition:all .14s; margin-bottom:3px; }
  .nmx .exp-item:hover { background:#161922; }
  .nmx .exp-item.on { background:#161922; border-color:#a78bfa; }
  .nmx .exp-item .num { font-size:10px; color:#a78bfa; font-weight:700; min-width:14px; }
  .nmx .exp-item .nm { font-size:11px; color:#cfd6da; line-height:1.4; }
  .nmx .exp-item.on .nm { color:#f3f3f8; }

  .nmx .main { min-width:0; }
  .nmx .exp-head { font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif; font-size:27px; font-weight:600; color:#f3f3f8; margin:0 0 4px; }
  .nmx .exp-sub { font-size:11px; color:#9aa0aa; letter-spacing:0.04em; margin-bottom:16px; }

  .nmx .secbar { display:flex; gap:6px; flex-wrap:wrap; margin-bottom:18px; border-bottom:1px solid #2a2a35; padding-bottom:12px; }
  .nmx .secbar .stab { background:#11131a; border:1px solid #2a2a35; color:#9aa0aa; padding:7px 12px; border-radius:8px; font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.08em; text-transform:uppercase; font-weight:700; cursor:pointer; transition:all .14s; }
  .nmx .secbar .stab:hover { border-color:#3a3a48; color:#e8e8ee; }
  .nmx .secbar .stab.on { background:#161922; border-color:#67e8f9; color:#67e8f9; }

  .nmx .exp { display:none; }
  .nmx .exp.on { display:block; }
  .nmx .sec { display:none; }
  .nmx .sec.on { display:block; }

  .nmx .prose { font-size:13px; color:#c4c8d0; line-height:1.72; max-width:860px; }
  .nmx .prose b { color:#f3f3f8; }
  .nmx .prose p { margin:0 0 12px; }
  .nmx .prose code, .nmx .eq { color:#fbbf24; background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #1c1c26; padding:2px 6px; border-radius:4px; font-size:12px; }
  .nmx .eqblock { background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #232330; border-radius:9px; padding:13px 15px; margin:13px 0; font-size:12.5px; color:#fbbf24; line-height:2; }
  .nmx ol.steps { font-size:13px; color:#c4c8d0; line-height:1.7; max-width:840px; padding-left:20px; }
  .nmx ol.steps li { margin-bottom:9px; }
  .nmx ol.steps li b { color:#f3f3f8; }
  .nmx ul.refs { list-style:none; padding:0; max-width:860px; }
  .nmx ul.refs li { font-size:12px; color:#9aa0aa; line-height:1.6; padding:8px 0; border-bottom:1px solid #1a1a24; }
  .nmx ul.refs li b { color:#cfd6da; }

  .nmx .layout { display:grid; grid-template-columns:minmax(0,1fr) 330px; gap:18px; align-items:start; }
  @media (max-width:1000px) { .nmx .layout { grid-template-columns:1fr; } }
  .nmx .panel { background:#11131a; border:1px solid #2a2a35; border-radius:12px; padding:16px; }
  .nmx .panel h3 { font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.16em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#67e8f9; font-weight:700; margin:0 0 13px; display:flex; align-items:center; justify-content:space-between; gap:8px; }
  .nmx canvas { display:block; width:100%; background:#08080b; border:1px solid #232330; border-radius:10px; }
  .nmx .row { display:flex; gap:9px; align-items:center; margin-bottom:11px; flex-wrap:wrap; }
  .nmx .row > label { font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#9aa0aa; min-width:58px; }
  .nmx input[type=range] { -webkit-appearance:none; appearance:none; background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #2a2a35; height:6px; border-radius:4px; flex:1; min-width:90px; }
  .nmx input[type=range]::-webkit-slider-thumb { -webkit-appearance:none; appearance:none; width:14px; height:14px; border-radius:50%; background:#a78bfa; cursor:pointer; border:none; }
  .nmx input[type=range]::-moz-range-thumb { width:14px; height:14px; border-radius:50%; background:#a78bfa; cursor:pointer; border:none; }
  .nmx input[type=number], .nmx input[type=text] { background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #2a2a35; color:#e8e8ee; padding:7px 9px; border-radius:6px; font-family:inherit; font-size:12px; }
  .nmx input[type=number] { width:74px; }
  .nmx input.fn { width:100%; flex:1; min-width:120px; color:#86efac; }
  .nmx input.bad { border-color:#fca5a5; color:#fca5a5; }
  .nmx select { background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #2a2a35; color:#e8e8ee; padding:7px 9px; border-radius:6px; font-family:inherit; font-size:11.5px; flex:1; min-width:120px; }
  .nmx .val { font-size:11.5px; color:#a78bfa; min-width:48px; text-align:right; }
  .nmx .btn { background:#a78bfa; color:#16091f; padding:9px 13px; border:none; border-radius:7px; font-family:inherit; font-size:10.5px; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.06em; text-transform:uppercase; cursor:pointer; }
  .nmx .btn:hover { background:#bda3ff; }
  .nmx .btn:disabled { opacity:0.4; cursor:not-allowed; }
  .nmx .btn.ghost { background:transparent; color:#cfd6da; border:1px solid #2a2a35; }
  .nmx .btn.ghost:hover { border-color:#a78bfa; color:#a78bfa; }
  .nmx .btn.cyan { background:#67e8f9; color:#04161b; }
  .nmx .btn.cyan:hover { background:#8af0ff; }
  .nmx .btn.amber { background:#fbbf24; color:#1c1402; }
  .nmx .btn.amber:hover { background:#fcd34d; }
  .nmx .btn.green { background:#86efac; color:#06210f; }
  .nmx .btn.green:hover { background:#a7f3c4; }
  .nmx .btn.red { background:#fca5a5; color:#260808; }
  .nmx .btn.red:hover { background:#fda4af; }
  .nmx .btns { display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; gap:8px; margin-top:6px; }
  .nmx .btns.three { grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr; }
  .nmx .btns .full { grid-column:1/-1; }
  .nmx .stats { display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; gap:8px; margin-top:13px; }
  .nmx .stat { background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #232330; border-radius:7px; padding:8px 10px; }
  .nmx .stat .k { font-size:9px; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#9aa0aa; }
  .nmx .stat .v { font-size:15px; color:#67e8f9; font-weight:700; margin-top:3px; word-break:break-word; }
  .nmx .stat .v.sm { font-size:12px; }
  .nmx .stat .v.green { color:#86efac; }
  .nmx .stat .v.amber { color:#fbbf24; }
  .nmx .stat .v.purple { color:#a78bfa; }
  .nmx .help { font-size:10.5px; color:#9aa0aa; line-height:1.65; margin-top:11px; }
  .nmx .help b { color:#e8e8ee; }
  .nmx .help code { color:#fbbf24; background:#0a0a0c; padding:1px 5px; border-radius:3px; }
  .nmx .seg { display:flex; gap:6px; flex-wrap:wrap; }
  .nmx .seg .opt { flex:1; text-align:center; background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #2a2a35; color:#9aa0aa; padding:7px 6px; border-radius:6px; font-size:10px; letter-spacing:0.06em; text-transform:uppercase; cursor:pointer; min-width:60px; }
  .nmx .seg .opt.on { border-color:#fbbf24; color:#fbbf24; }
  .nmx .tablewrap { margin-top:13px; max-height:230px; overflow:auto; border:1px solid #232330; border-radius:8px; }
  .nmx table.it { width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:10.5px; }
  .nmx table.it th { position:sticky; top:0; background:#11131a; color:#67e8f9; text-align:right; padding:6px 9px; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.04em; border-bottom:1px solid #2a2a35; white-space:nowrap; }
  .nmx table.it td { text-align:right; padding:4px 9px; color:#cfd6da; border-bottom:1px solid #14141c; white-space:nowrap; }
  .nmx table.it tr:last-child td { border-bottom:none; }
  .nmx table.it tr.cur td { background:rgba(167,139,250,0.10); color:#e8e8ee; }
  .nmx table.it tr.done td { color:#86efac; }
  .nmx .mtx { font-size:11px; color:#cfd6da; line-height:1.7; background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #232330; border-radius:8px; padding:10px 12px; margin-top:11px; overflow-x:auto; }
  .nmx .mtx .mrow { white-space:pre; font-variant-numeric:tabular-nums; }
  .nmx .mtx .piv { color:#fbbf24; }
  .nmx .log { background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #232330; border-radius:8px; padding:9px 11px; margin-top:13px; max-height:150px; overflow-y:auto; font-size:11px; color:#9aa0aa; line-height:1.7; }
  .nmx .log .ln { border-bottom:1px solid #14141c; padding:2px 0; }
  .nmx .log .ln:last-child { border-bottom:none; }
  .nmx .log .ln b { color:#67e8f9; }
  .nmx .log .ln.ok b { color:#86efac; }
  .nmx .log .ln.warn b { color:#fbbf24; }
  .nmx .ptlist { font-size:11px; color:#cfd6da; line-height:1.7; margin-top:10px; max-height:120px; overflow:auto; }
  .nmx .ptlist .pt { display:inline-block; background:#0a0a0c; border:1px solid #232330; border-radius:5px; padding:3px 7px; margin:0 5px 5px 0; }
  .nmx .ptlist .pt b { color:#a78bfa; }
  .nmx .badge { display:inline-block; font-size:9px; padding:2px 7px; border-radius:4px; background:#1a1a25; color:#86efac; letter-spacing:0.1em; }
  .nmx .badge.warn { color:#fbbf24; }
  .nmx .badge.bad { color:#fca5a5; }

  /* self-assessment */
  .nmx .quiz { max-width:860px; }
  .nmx .q { background:#11131a; border:1px solid #2a2a35; border-radius:10px; padding:14px 16px; margin-bottom:13px; }
  .nmx .q .qt { font-size:13px; color:#f3f3f8; line-height:1.55; margin-bottom:11px; }
  .nmx .q .qt b { color:#a78bfa; }
  .nmx .opt-a { display:block; padding:9px 12px; border:1px solid #2a2a35; border-radius:7px; margin-bottom:7px; font-size:12.5px; color:#cfd6da; cursor:pointer; transition:all .12s; }
  .nmx .opt-a:hover { border-color:#3a3a48; }
  .nmx .opt-a.sel { border-color:#67e8f9; color:#67e8f9; }
  .nmx .opt-a.correct { border-color:#86efac; background:rgba(134,239,172,0.08); color:#86efac; }
  .nmx .opt-a.wrong { border-color:#fca5a5; background:rgba(252,165,165,0.08); color:#fca5a5; }
  .nmx .q .expl { font-size:11.5px; color:#9aa0aa; line-height:1.6; margin-top:8px; padding-top:8px; border-top:1px solid #1c1c26; display:none; }
  .nmx .q .expl.show { display:block; }
  .nmx .q .expl b { color:#86efac; }
  .nmx .q.bad .expl b { color:#fca5a5; }
  .nmx .quizfoot { display:flex; align-items:center; gap:12px; margin-top:6px; }
  .nmx .quizfoot .score { font-size:11px; color:#9aa0aa; }
  .nmx .quizfoot .score b { color:#86efac; }
</style>
<main class="nmx">
  <div class="wrap">
    <a class="back" href="/aquintutor/labs">&#8592; All virtual labs</a>
    <div class="eyebrow">Numerical Methods &middot; Virtual lab</div>
    <h1>Roots, interpolation, quadrature, ODEs &amp; <em>linear systems</em></h1>
    <p class="lede">Six self-contained experiments, each a genuinely working numerical engine written in plain JavaScript &mdash; no libraries. You type a real function f(x) (parsed by a hand-rolled tokenizer and recursive-descent evaluator) and every control drives the computation: iterations animate, convergence and error are tabulated per step, and the exact value is compared against the numerical estimate. Pick an experiment on the left, then move through Aim, Theory, Procedure, the live Simulation, a graded Self-assessment, and References.</p>

    <div class="shell">
      <!-- ===================== SIDEBAR ===================== -->
      <aside class="sidebar">
        <div class="stitle">Experiments</div>
        <div class="exp-item on" data-exp="1"><span class="num">1</span><span class="nm">Root finding &mdash; bisection / Newton / secant / false-position</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="2"><span class="num">2</span><span class="nm">Interpolation &mdash; Lagrange &amp; Newton divided differences</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="3"><span class="num">3</span><span class="nm">Integration &mdash; trapezoidal, Simpson 1/3 &amp; 3/8</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="4"><span class="num">4</span><span class="nm">ODE solvers &mdash; Euler, Heun &amp; RK4</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="5"><span class="num">5</span><span class="nm">Linear systems &mdash; Gauss, LU &amp; Gauss-Seidel</span></div>
        <div class="exp-item" data-exp="6"><span class="num">6</span><span class="nm">Least-squares curve fitting</span></div>
      </aside>

      <!-- ===================== MAIN PANEL ===================== -->
      <div class="main">

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 1 — ROOT FINDING ============ -->
        <section class="exp on" id="exp-1">
          <h2 class="exp-head">1 &middot; Root finding</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Bisection, Newton-Raphson, secant and false-position on your own f(x), with animated iterates and per-step error</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To solve f(x)&nbsp;=&nbsp;0 for a chosen continuous function using four classical iterative methods, to watch each iterate converge on the canvas, and to compare their convergence orders by tabulating the approximate error at every step.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p><b>Bisection</b> brackets a root between a and b with f(a)&middot;f(b)&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;0 and halves the interval each step, keeping the half that still changes sign. It always converges (linearly), gaining one bit per iteration: the error bound is (b&minus;a)/2 to the power n.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Bisection: c = (a + b) / 2, keep [a,c] if f(a)f(c) &lt; 0 else [c,b]</div>
            <p><b>Newton-Raphson</b> uses the tangent line. From the Taylor expansion, the next iterate is the x-intercept of the tangent at the current point. It converges quadratically near a simple root but needs the derivative and can diverge.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Newton: x(n+1) = x(n) &minus; f(x(n)) / f'(x(n))</div>
            <p>The <b>secant</b> method replaces f' by a finite-difference slope through the last two points, giving superlinear order about 1.618 without needing a derivative. <b>False position (regula falsi)</b> uses the same secant formula but, like bisection, keeps a sign-changing bracket, so it is guaranteed to converge.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Secant / false-position: x(n+1) = x(n) &minus; f(x(n))&middot;(x(n) &minus; x(n&minus;1)) / (f(x(n)) &minus; f(x(n&minus;1)))</div>
            <p>The <b>approximate relative error</b> reported each step is |x(n+1) &minus; x(n)| / |x(n+1)|; iteration stops when it falls below the tolerance or the iteration cap is reached.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b>. A default function and bracket are loaded.</li>
            <li>Edit <b>f(x)</b> (for example <code>x^3 - x - 2</code>, <code>cos(x) - x</code>, <code>exp(-x) - x</code>). The plot redraws live; a red box means the expression failed to parse.</li>
            <li>Choose a <b>method</b>. For bracketing methods set <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> so the curve crosses between them; for open methods set the start point(s).</li>
            <li>Set the <b>tolerance</b> and <b>max iterations</b>, then press <b>Run</b>. Watch the iterate markers march toward the root.</li>
            <li>Read the per-step table: the current estimate, f(x) and the approximate error. Note how Newton roughly doubles the number of correct digits each step while bisection halves the bracket.</li>
            <li>Press <b>Step</b> to advance one iteration at a time, or <b>Reset</b> to clear.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Function &amp; iterates</span><span class="badge" id="rfStat">ready</span></h3>
                <canvas id="rfCv" width="680" height="430"></canvas>
                <div class="help"><b>Tip:</b> use <code>^</code> for powers, and functions <code>sin cos tan exp log sqrt abs</code>. Constants <code>pi</code> and <code>e</code> are available. The dashed grey line is y&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.</div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Controls</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>f(x)</label><input type="text" class="fn" id="rfFn" value="x^3 - x - 2"></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Method</label>
                    <select id="rfMethod">
                      <option value="bisect">Bisection</option>
                      <option value="newton">Newton-Raphson</option>
                      <option value="secant">Secant</option>
                      <option value="falsi">False position</option>
                    </select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row" id="rfBrow1"><label>a / x0</label><input type="number" id="rfA" value="1" step="0.1"><label style="min-width:40px">b / x1</label><input type="number" id="rfB" value="2" step="0.1"></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Tol</label><input type="number" id="rfTol" value="0.000001" step="0.000001"><label style="min-width:40px">Max</label><input type="number" id="rfMax" value="40" step="1"></div>
                  <div class="btns three">
                    <button class="btn" id="rfRun">Run</button>
                    <button class="btn cyan" id="rfStep">Step</button>
                    <button class="btn ghost" id="rfReset">Reset</button>
                  </div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Root est.</div><div class="v green" id="rfRoot">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">f(root)</div><div class="v sm" id="rfFval">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Iterations</div><div class="v purple" id="rfIters">0</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Rel. error</div><div class="v amber sm" id="rfErr">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="tablewrap">
                    <table class="it"><thead><tr><th>n</th><th id="rfH1">a</th><th id="rfH2">b</th><th>x</th><th>f(x)</th><th>err</th></tr></thead><tbody id="rfBody"></tbody></table>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="1"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Burden &amp; Faires</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis, 9th ed., Ch. 2 (Solutions of Equations in One Variable). Brooks/Cole.</li>
            <li><b>Atkinson</b> &mdash; An Introduction to Numerical Analysis, 2nd ed., Sec. 2. Wiley.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis: Root Finding, nalwss-coep.vlabs.ac.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 2 — INTERPOLATION ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-2">
          <h2 class="exp-head">2 &middot; Polynomial interpolation</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Lagrange and Newton divided-difference polynomials through your data points, drawn as a continuous curve</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To construct the unique polynomial of degree at most n through n+1 given points using both the Lagrange and the Newton divided-difference forms, to confirm the two forms give the same curve, and to estimate the value of the interpolant at any query point.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>Given n+1 distinct points there is exactly one polynomial of degree at most n passing through all of them. The <b>Lagrange form</b> writes it as a weighted sum of basis polynomials, each of which is one at its own node and zero at every other node.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">P(x) = sum over i of y(i) &middot; L(i, x),  L(i, x) = product over j not equal to i of (x &minus; x(j)) / (x(i) &minus; x(j))</div>
            <p>The <b>Newton divided-difference form</b> builds the same polynomial incrementally, so adding a point costs only one extra term. The coefficients are the leading divided differences computed from a triangular table.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">P(x) = f[x0] + f[x0,x1](x &minus; x0) + f[x0,x1,x2](x &minus; x0)(x &minus; x1) + ...<br>f[x(i),...,x(i+k)] = ( f[x(i+1),...] &minus; f[x(i),...] ) / ( x(i+k) &minus; x(i) )</div>
            <p>Both are exact at the nodes; between them they can oscillate (Runge phenomenon) for high degree on equally spaced data. The interpolation error involves the (n+1)-th derivative of the true function and the node product.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b>. Several points are preloaded and the interpolating polynomial is drawn through them.</li>
            <li><b>Click on the canvas</b> to add a point, or use <b>x</b>, <b>y</b> and <b>Add point</b>. Use <b>Random</b> or <b>Clear</b> to reshape the data set.</li>
            <li>Toggle <b>Lagrange</b> and <b>Newton</b>; both curves should coincide exactly &mdash; they are the same polynomial in two algebraic dresses.</li>
            <li>Enter a <b>query x</b> and read the interpolated value; a vertical marker shows it on the curve.</li>
            <li>Read the printed <b>divided-difference table</b> &mdash; its top row gives the Newton coefficients.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Interpolant</span><span class="badge" id="ipStat">0 points</span></h3>
                <canvas id="ipCv" width="680" height="430"></canvas>
                <div class="help"><b>Click</b> the plot to drop a point. The polynomial has degree = points &minus; 1. Watch for wild swings between widely spaced nodes &mdash; that is the Runge phenomenon.</div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Data &amp; query</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>x</label><input type="number" id="ipX" value="0" step="0.1"><label style="min-width:30px">y</label><input type="number" id="ipY" value="0" step="0.1"><button class="btn" id="ipAdd">Add</button></div>
                  <div class="btns three">
                    <button class="btn ghost" id="ipRand">Random</button>
                    <button class="btn ghost" id="ipUndo">Undo</button>
                    <button class="btn red" id="ipClear">Clear</button>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row" style="margin-top:12px"><label>Form</label>
                    <div class="seg" style="flex:1">
                      <div class="opt on" data-ipform="both">Both</div>
                      <div class="opt" data-ipform="lagrange">Lagrange</div>
                      <div class="opt" data-ipform="newton">Newton</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Query x</label><input type="number" id="ipQ" value="2.5" step="0.1"><span class="val" id="ipQv">P = --</span></div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Points</div><div class="v purple" id="ipN">0</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Degree</div><div class="v" id="ipDeg">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="help" style="margin-top:13px"><b>Divided-difference table</b> (Newton coefficients along the top diagonal):</div>
                  <div class="mtx" id="ipDD"></div>
                  <div class="ptlist" id="ipList"></div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="2"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Burden &amp; Faires</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis, 9th ed., Ch. 3 (Interpolation and Polynomial Approximation). Brooks/Cole.</li>
            <li><b>Hildebrand</b> &mdash; Introduction to Numerical Analysis, 2nd ed., Ch. 2. Dover.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis: Interpolation, nalwss-coep.vlabs.ac.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 3 — INTEGRATION ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-3">
          <h2 class="exp-head">3 &middot; Numerical integration</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Trapezoidal, Simpson 1/3 and Simpson 3/8 quadrature with drawn panels and error against the reference value</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To approximate a definite integral of f(x) over [a,b] by the composite trapezoidal, Simpson one-third and Simpson three-eighths rules, to visualise the approximating panels, and to study how the error shrinks as the number of subintervals grows.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>A Newton-Cotes rule replaces f by an interpolating polynomial on each panel and integrates that exactly. With h = (b&minus;a)/n the <b>composite trapezoidal rule</b> joins consecutive points by straight lines:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">T = (h/2) [ f0 + 2(f1 + f2 + ... + f(n&minus;1)) + fn ],  error ~ O(h squared)</div>
            <p><b>Simpson's 1/3 rule</b> fits a parabola over each pair of panels (so n must be even) and is exact for cubics:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">S1/3 = (h/3) [ f0 + 4(f1+f3+...) + 2(f2+f4+...) + fn ],  error ~ O(h to the 4)</div>
            <p><b>Simpson's 3/8 rule</b> fits a cubic over each group of three panels (n a multiple of 3):</p>
            <div class="eqblock">S3/8 = (3h/8) [ f0 + 3(f1+f2) + 3(f4+f5) + ... + 2(f3+f6+...) + fn ]</div>
            <p>The reported error is the absolute difference from a high-resolution reference value (Simpson with many points), so you can watch the trapezoidal error fall like h squared while Simpson falls like h to the fourth.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b>. The default integrand and limits are loaded and the panels are shaded.</li>
            <li>Edit <b>f(x)</b>, the limits <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>, and the number of subintervals <b>n</b> with the slider.</li>
            <li>Pick a <b>rule</b>. For Simpson 1/3, n is rounded up to an even number; for 3/8, to a multiple of three (the panel says which).</li>
            <li>Read the <b>estimate</b>, the <b>reference</b> value and the <b>absolute error</b>.</li>
            <li>Increase n and watch the error drop &mdash; the panel reports the empirical order of accuracy as you do.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Quadrature panels</span><span class="badge" id="inStat">ready</span></h3>
                <canvas id="inCv" width="680" height="430"></canvas>
                <div class="help">Shaded regions are the panels actually summed. Straight tops mean trapezoidal; curved tops mean the fitted parabola or cubic of Simpson's rules.</div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Controls</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>f(x)</label><input type="text" class="fn" id="inFn" value="sin(x)"></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>a</label><input type="number" id="inA" value="0" step="0.1"><label style="min-width:20px">b</label><input type="number" id="inB" value="3.14159265" step="0.1"></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>n</label><input type="range" id="inN" min="2" max="100" value="8"><span class="val" id="inNv">8</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Rule</label>
                    <div class="seg" style="flex:1">
                      <div class="opt on" data-inrule="trap">Trapz</div>
                      <div class="opt" data-inrule="s13">Simp 1/3</div>
                      <div class="opt" data-inrule="s38">Simp 3/8</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Estimate</div><div class="v green" id="inEst">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Reference</div><div class="v sm" id="inRef">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Abs. error</div><div class="v amber sm" id="inErr">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Step h</div><div class="v sm" id="inH">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="help"><b>Effective n:</b> <span id="inNeff" style="color:#a78bfa">--</span> &middot; <b>empirical order p:</b> <span id="inOrder" style="color:#fbbf24">--</span></div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="3"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Burden &amp; Faires</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis, 9th ed., Ch. 4 (Numerical Differentiation and Integration). Brooks/Cole.</li>
            <li><b>Davis &amp; Rabinowitz</b> &mdash; Methods of Numerical Integration, 2nd ed. Academic Press.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis: Numerical Integration, nalwss-coep.vlabs.ac.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 4 — ODE SOLVERS ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-4">
          <h2 class="exp-head">4 &middot; ODE solvers</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Euler, Heun (improved Euler) and classical RK4 on dy/dx = f(x,y), against the analytic solution</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To integrate a first-order initial-value problem by the explicit Euler, Heun and fourth-order Runge-Kutta methods, to plot each numerical solution against the known analytic curve, and to compare their global errors as the step size changes.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>For dy/dx = f(x,y) with y(x0) = y0, a one-step method advances by h. <b>Euler's method</b> follows the slope at the start of the step &mdash; it is first order, so halving h roughly halves the error.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">Euler: y(n+1) = y(n) + h &middot; f(x(n), y(n))</div>
            <p><b>Heun's method</b> (improved Euler / RK2) averages the slope at the start with a predicted slope at the end, giving second order:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">k1 = f(x, y),  k2 = f(x+h, y + h&middot;k1)<br>y(n+1) = y(n) + (h/2)(k1 + k2)</div>
            <p><b>Classical RK4</b> takes a weighted average of four slope samples and is fourth order &mdash; halving h cuts the error by sixteen:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">k1 = f(x, y),  k2 = f(x+h/2, y+h&middot;k1/2)<br>k3 = f(x+h/2, y+h&middot;k2/2),  k4 = f(x+h, y+h&middot;k3)<br>y(n+1) = y(n) + (h/6)(k1 + 2k2 + 2k3 + k4)</div>
            <p>The panel reports the maximum absolute error against the analytic solution; choose a preset problem so the exact curve is known.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b> and pick a <b>preset ODE</b> &mdash; each comes with its analytic solution.</li>
            <li>Set the initial point <b>x0</b>, <b>y0</b>, the end <b>x</b> and the step <b>h</b> (or the number of steps).</li>
            <li>Enable the methods you want to compare. The analytic curve is the dashed green line; numerical solutions are coloured polylines.</li>
            <li>Read each method's <b>max error</b>. Halve h and confirm Euler error halves, Heun quarters, RK4 drops about sixteen-fold.</li>
            <li>Try a larger h to see Euler drift away while RK4 still tracks the true curve.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Solution curves</span><span class="badge" id="odStat">ready</span></h3>
                <canvas id="odCv" width="680" height="430"></canvas>
                <div class="help"><span style="color:#86efac">&mdash; &mdash;</span> analytic &nbsp; <span style="color:#fca5a5">&mdash;</span> Euler &nbsp; <span style="color:#fbbf24">&mdash;</span> Heun &nbsp; <span style="color:#67e8f9">&mdash;</span> RK4</div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Controls</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>ODE</label>
                    <select id="odPreset">
                      <option value="0">y' = y, y(0)=1 &middot; exact e^x</option>
                      <option value="1">y' = x + y, y(0)=1 &middot; exact 2e^x - x - 1</option>
                      <option value="2">y' = -2y, y(0)=1 &middot; exact e^(-2x)</option>
                      <option value="3">y' = x - y, y(0)=1 &middot; exact x-1+2e^(-x)</option>
                      <option value="4">y' = y - x^2 + 1, y(0)=0.5</option>
                      <option value="5">y' = cos(x), y(0)=0 &middot; exact sin x</option>
                    </select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>x0 / y0</label><input type="number" id="odX0" value="0" step="0.1"><input type="number" id="odY0" value="1" step="0.1"></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>end x</label><input type="number" id="odXe" value="2" step="0.1"><label style="min-width:14px">h</label><input type="number" id="odH" value="0.25" step="0.01"></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Show</label>
                    <div class="seg" style="flex:1">
                      <div class="opt on" data-odm="euler">Euler</div>
                      <div class="opt on" data-odm="heun">Heun</div>
                      <div class="opt on" data-odm="rk4">RK4</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Steps</div><div class="v purple" id="odSteps">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">y(end) RK4</div><div class="v green sm" id="odYend">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Euler max err</div><div class="v sm" id="odEe" style="color:#fca5a5">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Heun max err</div><div class="v sm" id="odEh" style="color:#fbbf24">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">RK4 max err</div><div class="v sm" id="odEr" style="color:#67e8f9">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Exact y(end)</div><div class="v sm" id="odExact">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="4"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Burden &amp; Faires</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis, 9th ed., Ch. 5 (Initial-Value Problems for ODEs). Brooks/Cole.</li>
            <li><b>Hairer, Norsett &amp; Wanner</b> &mdash; Solving Ordinary Differential Equations I, 2nd ed. Springer.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis: ODE Solvers, nalwss-coep.vlabs.ac.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 5 — LINEAR SYSTEMS ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-5">
          <h2 class="exp-head">5 &middot; Linear systems</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Gauss elimination with partial pivoting, LU decomposition and Gauss-Seidel iteration, with the steps shown</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To solve a square linear system Ax = b by Gaussian elimination with partial pivoting and by LU factorisation, then to solve it iteratively with Gauss-Seidel, displaying the intermediate matrices and the iterates so the mechanics of each method are visible.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p><b>Gaussian elimination</b> uses row operations to reduce A to upper-triangular form, then back-substitutes. <b>Partial pivoting</b> swaps in the row with the largest pivot magnitude at each column to limit round-off growth and avoid division by a tiny pivot.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">multiplier m = a(i,k) / a(k,k);  row i := row i &minus; m &middot; row k</div>
            <p><b>LU decomposition</b> records those multipliers in a unit lower-triangular L and the result in an upper-triangular U so that PA = LU. Solving then needs only a forward solve Ly = Pb and a back solve Ux = y &mdash; cheap to repeat for many right-hand sides.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">A = L U;  solve L y = b (forward), then U x = y (backward)</div>
            <p><b>Gauss-Seidel</b> is iterative: it updates each unknown in place using the most recent values of the others. It converges when A is diagonally dominant; the spectral radius of the iteration matrix governs the rate.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">x(i) := ( b(i) &minus; sum over j&ne;i of a(i,j) x(j) ) / a(i,i)</div>
            <p>The residual norm ||Ax &minus; b|| measures how well the current solution satisfies the system.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b>. A 3&times;3 system is preloaded; edit any entry of <b>A</b> or <b>b</b>.</li>
            <li>Choose <b>size</b> (2, 3 or 4) and use <b>Random</b> for a fresh diagonally dominant system, or <b>Reset</b>.</li>
            <li>Press <b>Gauss</b> to run elimination with partial pivoting &mdash; each pivot and row operation is logged and the triangular matrix is shown.</li>
            <li>Press <b>LU</b> to print L and U and the permutation; verify the solution matches Gauss.</li>
            <li>Press <b>Gauss-Seidel</b> to iterate; watch the iterates and the residual fall (the badge warns if the matrix is not diagonally dominant).</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3><span>Working &amp; steps</span><span class="badge" id="lsStat">ready</span></h3>
                <div class="row"><label>Size</label>
                  <div class="seg" style="flex:1">
                    <div class="opt" data-lsn="2">2&times;2</div>
                    <div class="opt on" data-lsn="3">3&times;3</div>
                    <div class="opt" data-lsn="4">4&times;4</div>
                  </div>
                  <button class="btn ghost" id="lsRand">Random</button>
                  <button class="btn ghost" id="lsReset">Reset</button>
                </div>
                <div id="lsMatrix" style="margin-top:6px"></div>
                <div class="btns three" style="margin-top:10px">
                  <button class="btn" id="lsGauss">Gauss</button>
                  <button class="btn cyan" id="lsLU">LU decomp</button>
                  <button class="btn amber" id="lsGS">Gauss-Seidel</button>
                </div>
                <div class="log" id="lsLog" style="max-height:300px"></div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Solution</h3>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Method</div><div class="v sm purple" id="lsMethod">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">det(A)</div><div class="v sm" id="lsDet">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="mtx" id="lsSol" style="margin-top:11px">solution vector x will appear here</div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Residual ||Ax-b||</div><div class="v amber sm" id="lsRes">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Diag. dominant</div><div class="v sm" id="lsDom">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row" style="margin-top:11px"><label>GS iters</label><input type="number" id="lsGSit" value="30" step="1"><label style="min-width:36px">tol</label><input type="number" id="lsGStol" value="0.000001" step="0.000001"></div>
                  <div class="mtx" id="lsGSiter" style="margin-top:6px;max-height:180px;overflow:auto"></div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="5"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Golub &amp; Van Loan</b> &mdash; Matrix Computations, 4th ed., Ch. 3 (General Linear Systems). Johns Hopkins.</li>
            <li><b>Burden &amp; Faires</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis, 9th ed., Ch. 6 &amp; 7. Brooks/Cole.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Numerical Analysis: Systems of Linear Equations, nalwss-coep.vlabs.ac.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 6 — LEAST SQUARES ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-6">
          <h2 class="exp-head">6 &middot; Least-squares curve fitting</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Fit a line or a polynomial of chosen degree to scattered points by solving the normal equations</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To fit a polynomial of chosen degree to scattered, noisy data in the least-squares sense by forming and solving the normal equations, and to read off the residual sum of squares and the coefficient of determination R squared.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>Least squares chooses coefficients that minimise the sum of squared vertical residuals between the model and the data. For a degree-m polynomial the model is a linear combination of the powers of x, so minimising leads to the <b>normal equations</b> &mdash; a square system in the unknown coefficients.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">minimise S = sum of ( y(i) &minus; P(x(i)) ) squared<br>normal equations: (X transpose X) c = X transpose y</div>
            <p>Here X is the Vandermonde-style design matrix whose columns are 1, x, x squared, and so on. For a straight line this reduces to the familiar slope and intercept formulas.</p>
            <div class="eqblock">line: slope = ( n&middot;Sxy &minus; Sx&middot;Sy ) / ( n&middot;Sxx &minus; Sx squared ),  intercept = ( Sy &minus; slope&middot;Sx ) / n</div>
            <p>Goodness of fit is summarised by R squared = 1 &minus; SS_res / SS_tot, which is one for a perfect fit and falls toward zero as the model explains less of the variance. Raising the degree always lowers SS_res but risks over-fitting the noise.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open <b>Simulation</b>. A scatter of noisy points is preloaded and a fit is drawn through it.</li>
            <li><b>Click</b> to add points, or press <b>Generate</b> to sample a known curve plus noise; use <b>Clear</b> to start over.</li>
            <li>Set the <b>degree</b> (1 = straight line). The fitted curve and its equation update immediately.</li>
            <li>Read the printed <b>coefficients</b>, the <b>residual sum of squares</b> and <b>R squared</b>.</li>
            <li>Raise the degree and watch R squared climb toward one while the curve starts to chase individual points &mdash; the signature of over-fitting.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
